Question: this keyword in JavaScript. Quick answer: this keyword is referencing the current execution context. Longer answer: this works differently depending on where it was called. If you use this in the global context, it will reference the window object in the browser and the global object in the node. // browser console.log(window.a) // undefined this.a = 1 console.log(window.a) // 1
// node console.log(global.a) // undefined this.a = 1 console.log(global.a) // 1
